ing to work towards a better future for all.\u003c/p\u003e","paraWordCount":68,"blockQuote":"","blockQuoteMedia":{},"visibleLines":0,"isVideoData":false,"titleSlug":"untitled-entry-2023-12-20-at-10-24-49","publicationIndex":false,"backgroundColor":"","mediaWidth":"DEFAULT","mediaNew":[],"contextData":{"apiContext":{"primaryPillar":"Pillar: Net Zero \u0026 Energy","tenant":"sustainability","pageLogo":"/sustainability/images/cmpimg_00001","keywords":["Net zero ","energy","sustainability "],"slogan":"A forum to advance sustainability solutions and accelerate world-changing impact","brand":"The Sustainability Project","pageContentType":"addPublication","componentTimeStamp":"2025-04-09T20:09:59.295Z","slug":"top-5-sustainability-wins-in-2023"}}},{"internalName":"bPG__1-Ecosystems","type":"blockParagraph","title":"1. Ecosystems","paragraph":"\u003cp\u003eA landmark European Union anti-deforestation regulation came into force in June 2023. The \u003ca href=\"https://environment.ec.europa.eu/topics/forests/deforestation/regulation-deforestation-free-products_en\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eEU’s deforestation-free regulation\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e (EUDR) aims to prevent seven forest-related commodities and their products from entering the EU market if they’re found to be linked to deforestation. Approximately 420m hectares of the world’s forests have been lost to agricultural land since 1990—an area bigger than all the EU nations put together—according to the UN Food and Agriculture Organisation. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eDevised to preserve our CO2-storing forests, reduce greenhouse-gas emissions and prevent biodiversity loss, EUDR stipulates that from the end of 2024, any goods placed on the EU market, whether from inside the region or exported from countries beyond it, must have been produced on land where neither deforestation nor forest degradation occurred after December 2020. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eWhat it means for companies is that those trading in the regulated commodities and derivatives (eg, timber, cocoa, beef, palm oil), a list that will be regularly updated, must undertake due diligence across their supply chain, extending to global suppliers. Through this framework companies will confirm on an annual basis that they comply with the new law to protect forests, while also avoiding the risk of penalties that noncompliance incurs, potentially fines of up to\u003cb\u003e \u003c/b\u003e4% of their EU turnover.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eBecause sustainable practices also impact society, companies’ compliance with land, labour and human-rights laws—including those of Indigenous communities—in their suppliers’ countries is also subject to transparent due-diligence statements.\u003c/p\u003e","paraWordCount":231,"blockQuote":"","blockQuoteMedia":{},"visibleLines":0,"isVideoData":false,"titleSlug":"1-ecosystems","publicationIndex":false,"backgroundColor":"","mediaWidth":"DEFAULT","mediaNew":[],"contextData":{"apiContext":{"primaryPillar":"Pillar: Net Zero \u0026 Energy","tenant":"sustainability","pageLogo":"/sustainability/images/cmpimg_00001","keywords":["Net zero ","energy","sustainability "],"slogan":"A forum to advance sustainability solutions and accelerate world-changing impact","brand":"The Sustainability Project","pageContentType":"addPublication","componentTimeStamp":"2025-04-09T20:09:59.295Z","slug":"top-5-sustainability-wins-in-2023"}}},{"internalName":"bPG__2-Net-zero-and-energy","type":"blockParagraph","title":"2. Net zero and energy","paragraph":"\u003cp\u003eWorldwide investment in clean energy has grown by 40%, according to the International Energy Agency (IEA), a global forecaster. This means that as more households, businesses and organisations switch to using electric vehicles, solar power and heat pumps during a global energy crisis that has seen fuel prices escalate, the demand for fossil fuels could peak by 2030. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eThe IEA’s \u003ca href=\"https://www.iea.org/reports/world-energy-outlook-2023\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eWorld Energy Outlook 2023\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e cites “an accelerating pace of change”, with positive examples including the $1bn per day currently being spent deploying solar energy. Clean energy is “the most dynamic aspect of global energy investment,” the report states in its key findings.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eHowever, the IEA emphasises that public policy which supports the development of a clean energy system and the phasing-out of inefficient polluting assets is crucial if the Net Zero Emissions Scenario by 2050 is to be achievable. Global carbon-dioxide emissions from burning coal, oil and gas have reached a new record and are set to have risen at a faster rate in 2023 than the 10-year average, according to \u003ca href=\"https://globalcarbonbudget.org/fossil-co2-emissions-at-record-high-in-2023/\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eGlobal Carbon Budget\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e, a research consortium.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003ePositively, the \u003ca href=\"https://impact.economist.com/sustainability/net-zero-and-energy/cop28-dispatch-december-14th-2023\"\u003e\u003cu\u003eCOP28 climate talks\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e in Dubai ended, for the first time, with an agreement to move away from using fossil fuels for energy. This shift, \u003ca href=\"https://unfccc.int/news/cop28-agreement-signals-beginning-of-the-end-of-the-fossil-fuel-era\"\u003e\u003cu\u003ethe agreement said\u003c/u\u003e\u003c/a\u003e, should be accelerated “in this critical decade”, “in keeping with science”. While the final text will not satisfy all—it does signify the beginning of the end for fossil fuels. The summit has achieved other wins including action on methane emissions and calls to triple renewables deployment and establish a loss and damage fund.\u003c/p\u003e","paraWordCount":260,"blockQuote":"","blockQuoteMedia":{},"visibleLines":0,"isVideoData":false,"titleSlug":"2-net-zero-and-energy","publicationIndex":false,"backgroundColor":"","mediaWidth":"DEFAULT","mediaNew":[],"contextData":{"apiContext":{"primaryPillar":"Pillar: Net Zero \u0026 Energy","tenant":"sustainability","pageLogo":"/sustainability/images/cmpimg_00001","keywords":["Net zero ","energy","sustainability "],"slogan":"A forum to advance sustainability solutions and accelerate world-changing impact","brand":"The Sustainability Project","pageContentType":"addPublication","componentTimeStamp":"2025-04-09T20:09:59.295Z","slug":"top-5-sustainability-wins-in-2023"}}},{"internalName":"bPG__3-Reducing-plastics","type":"blockParagraph","title":"3. Reducing plastics","paragraph":"\u003cp\u003eAre we edging towards a plastic-free future? Last month in Nairobi, an international treaty to defeat plastic pollution was discussed by the Intergovernmental Negotiating Committee at its third session (INC-3), whose goal is to strike agreement on an international legally binding instrument on plastic pollution by the end of next year. The INC’s first session was held in Uruguay in November last year, and the second in France in May this year. The next round of draft discussions is due to take place in Canada in April 2024.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eThis represents progress, although there is still much work to be done because plastic pollution is a global disaster: more than 430m tonnes are being produced every year, and the majority of that ends up as landfill or entering our oceans and the food chain. The financial cost of this environmental, economic and human-health crisis is estimated between $300bn and $600bn a year. The most achievable changes, the INC organisers say, come from behavioural change—a shift from our current “throwaway economy” to a “reuse economy.”\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eAhead of the recent talks, the INC’s president, Gustavo Meza-Cuadra Velasquez said: “We are entering a very important phase of our negotiations… For the first time we are entering a discussion with a text\u003cb\u003e.\u003c/b\u003e” \u003c/p\u003e","paraWordCount":205,"blockQuote":"","blockQuoteMedia":{},"visibleLines":0,"isVideoData":false,"titleSlug":"3-reducing-plastics","publicationIndex":false,"backgroundColor":"","mediaWidth":"DEFAULT","mediaNew":[],"contextData":{"apiContext":{"primaryPillar":"Pillar: Net Zero \u0026 Energy","tenant":"sustainability","pageLogo":"/sustainability/images/cmpimg_00001","keywords":["Net zero ","energy","sustainability "],"slogan":"A forum to advance sustainability solutions and accelerate world-changing impact","brand":"The Sustainability Project","pageContentType":"addPublication","componentTimeStamp":"2025-04-09T20:09:59.295Z","slug":"top-5-sustainability-wins-in-2023"}}},{"internalName":"bPG__4-Climate-finance","type":"blockParagraph","title":"4. Climate finance","paragraph":"\u003cp\u003eDuring COP28 in Dubai this month, the Green Climate Fund received six new pledges. The US, Australia, Switzerland, Italy, Portugal and Estonia are the latest to align with the world’s biggest climate fund, which operates under the Paris agreement, bringing the total amount pledged over the next four years to $12.8bn, up from $9.3bn. \u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eFurther contributions are expected as momentum grows. GFC calls climate financing “the true enabler of climate action,” and Mafalda Duarte, its executive director, has declared “a new era for the Green Climate Fund and the investments we need for a future we all deserve.”\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eIn practical terms, this additional funding means that in the next GFC programming cycle, 2024-27, developing countries will receive more resources to help protect and educate their vulnerable communities about the impacts of climate change, such as extreme weather events that can result in flooding, heatwaves and drought.\u003c/p\u003e","paraWordCount":144,"blockQuote":"","blockQuoteMedia":{},"visibleLines":0,"isVideoData":false,"titleSlug":"4-climate-finance","publicationIndex":false,"backgroundColor":"","mediaWidth":"DEFAULT","mediaNew":[],"contextData":{"apiContext"